@NODE NOMANUAL

You don't have to. Just try typing in shell

    @{b} ButtonBar Example-menu @{ub}

and experiment. It really should not be difficult.

@ENDNODE
@NODE SHORT

Use this program to create your button interfaces for your work.
Each button executes a command specified by you.

@ENDNODE
@NODE MOTIVATION

When you work on something, you need to run a lof  of  different  programs  with
unusual  parameters.  It  would  be  odd  to  put  the  list  of weird seemingly
unconnected programs in ToolsDaemon menu (which is the program I use mainly)  so
you  may  want  to create dedicated menu sitting on the screen (unlike the menus
that need the right mouse button to be visible).

Of course, you can use this program instead of ToolsDaemon, but
honestly, ToolsDaemon is neater.

@ENDNODE
@NODE REQUIREMENTS
ButtonBar requires "wbstart.library" V2.0+.

If you are not going to launch programs from WB, but only from CLI and
scripts, you don't actually need it. Most of WB programs can be run from
CLI anyway, but sometimes it is not convenient.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "CLI USAGE"
ButtonBar MENUFILE/M,PORT/K
 
@{"Menufile" link "SYNTAX OF MENUFILE"} is the file containing definition of all buttons, which is
what text buttons show, what keys are assigned to buttons (if any) and
what each button actually do. If you don't supply menufile, "S:ButtonBar.menu"
will be taken instead. If you supply PORT argument, arexx port of that
name will be created. Notice that no arexx port is being created
without PORT argument being used.

Example: ButtonBar Games-menu PORT="BB-GAMES"

@ENDNODE
@NODE USAGE

@{t Mouse usage:}

o Press a button at the top row to open and close columns
o Press a button in a column to execute a command
o Press a button at the top row to edit column properties and manipulate
      columns
o Press a button in a column while holding Shift to edit button

@{t "Keyboard usage:"}

Use arrowkeys to move mouse cursor over the buttons. Use space or enter to press
the button. Esc key quits as well as Q key if not  redefined (see later).

@{t "Keyboard shortcuts:"}

You can define your own shortcuts to buttons. To do it, edit button by clicking
it while holding Shift and prefix the letter in the title you want to use as a
shortcut with underscore (_).

   @{e "Examples:"}

   _Edit source            defines shortcut e
   Edit _Picture           defines shortcut p

If there are ambiguous shortcuts, the topmost one found in the leftmost column
is used.


@{t Options}

All the options are @{i} local @{ui} to menu, that is every menu  has  it's  own
settings. You can change the settings in submenus of intuition menu
@{i}properties@{ui}.


@{h Properties/ButtonWidth}
   Change the width of buttons (in pixels)
@{h Properties/HotKey}
   Set hotkey (standard commodity form). On this hotkey ButtonBar will get
   activated.
@{h Properties/Prefix}
   Set so called prefix. When the prefix is set, it can be denoted in commands
   assigned to buttons by "\\x".

      @{i}Example@{ui}
      If prefix is "c:requestchoice", you can write
      '\\x "Choice" "Quit" "Yes" "No"'.

@{h Properties/Font}
   Select a font to be used by buttons.

@{h Properties/Booleans}
   Set a lot of mostly yes/no options. Explanation concerning truly boolean menus
is given for YES case.

@{t "Quit button present:"}
   At the left top of the column-menu a tiny "Quit" button appears

@{t "Open on workbench:"}
   Force ButtonBar to open on Workbench screen. If off, ButtonBar opens itself
   on frontmost screen.

@{t "Columns are exclusive:"}
   No more than one column may be open. That is - when you open new column,
   the old closes itself.

@{t "Take key from all columns:"}
   The shortcut key is taken from all columns, no matter whether they are open
   or not. In case of conflict the 'first' shortcut key is taken. If off, only
   shortcuts from open columns are taken.

@{t "Open columns on hot key:"}
   When the hotkey is pressed (if there @{e is} a hotkey) all columns will be
   opened.

@{t "Open columns down:"}
   The preffered direction of opening columns is down.

@{t "Columns mode:"}
   Affect the way columns are being closed

   @{e Unstable}    Once a button is pressed, column disappears
   @{e Stable}      Column stays open even if a button is pressed
   @{e Autoclose}   All columns disappear once some window outside
   @{e }            ButtonBar is activated
   @{e Forceopen}   Once the column is open, there's no way to close it

@{t "After button press"}
   Affects the way @{e whole} ButtoBar behaves after a button press.

   @{e Live}        ButtonBar stays on the screen
   @{e Die}         ButtonBar dies
   @{e Sleep}       ButtonBar disappears from the screen but can be awaken
               by ARREXX command WAKEUP

@ENDNODE
@NODE "SYNTAX OF MENUFILE"

All text coming before first menu-title is ignored. Control
sequences (they begin with \ like in TeX) are the exception, even
more they MUST come before first menu-title. That's why this doc can
serve as menufile.

There are two logical parts of menu file - first is part
before first menu-title, second is the rest.

First part may contain some ordinary text (like this doc) and also
control sequences, which control behaviour of buttonbar. They will be
listed later. Control sequences CANNOT be used in second part
except sequences that will be executed upon button-press.

Organization of second part:

Buttons are organized into menus. You start menu definition by
entering menu-title using ":menutitle". Next come your buttons.
Button has first line for name, second for path of the program
to be executed. Possible contents of second line:

  . CLI-command argument1 argument2 ...

    command will be executed from its directory from CLI. E.g.
    for 'Games:Bleble/Bleblal aha' first 'cd Games:Bleble/' will be
    made and then 'Bleblal aha' executed.

  . CLI-script argument1 argument2 ...

    Similar to above, except that script must have set flag S on.
    That's how ButtonBar tells, whether it is a script.

  . <WB> WB-program

    WB-program will be run from WorkBench using information stored in
    WB-program.info

  . SECOND-PART COMMAND - see later.

Line for name may be ended with |<key>. This way you can assign keys to
buttons. Use _ to underscore letters in buttonname. If you use _ for
underscoring, you don't need to use |. Character following _ will be
automatically considered key shorcut.

Please note, that you MUST enter path for all programs. This means
that you cannot write 'run <>nil: work:something'. Instead, you
have to write 'c:run <>nil: work:something'.

In second part everything you write has importance, except comments.
Comments lines start with ;, # or /. Also empty line (no characters
including spaces) is not significant.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "FIRST PART CONTROL SEQUENCES"

\\position <x>,<y>       coordinates of the bar.
\\font <name>,<height>   used font. This file may or maynot end in
                        .font
\\buttonwidth <width>    width to be used by buttons. Default is 90.
\\stablebar              this is a switch. It makes menubar not
                        disappear when button executed.
\\quitbutton             small quitbutton on the left will appear
\\openmenu <i>           menu number {i} will be opened on the start.
                        This sequence can be specified more times
                        to open more menus.
\\openmenu all           all menus will be opened on the start. but
                        in exclusive mode (see below) finally right
                        one menu will be open.
\\exclusivemenus         Only one menu can be open at the time
\\fixedopen              this option forces all menus to stay open
                        once they were opened.
\\opendown               sets prefered direction of menus. Default
                        is up.

\\runanddie              once some button is executed, buttonbar quits.
                        This allows buttonbar to be used instead of
                        multichoice (buttonbar has key support, which
                        is not the case of multichoice.

\\hotkey <key>           allows assigning standard commodities hotkey to
                        the buttonbar. This doesnot work, if more
                        buttonbars are running. (TO BE FIXED)

\\workbench              this will force ButtonBar to be opened on Workbech
                        screen. Otherwise ButtonBar opens on front-most
                        screen.

\\prefix <prefix>        sets string, which will be attached to commands
                        startinf with \x. It can be thought of as macro

These control sequences are used WITHOUT the space between \ and
the rest. We put a space here so that these sequences don't actually
work!

@ENDNODE
@NODE "SECOND PART COMMANDS"

\\quit                   "quit" function.

\\restart                "restart" function. Good for seeing effect
                        of changed menufile.

\\print <string>         this will print string to standard output.
                        Using this command ButtonBar can behave
                        like Commodore's RequestChoice, but with
                        key support. Typical usage:

                        set var=`buttonbar t:menu`

                        where in menu, to each button only commands
                        \print 1, \print 2 etc. are assigned.
                        As you may have noticed, RequestChoice is
                        ESSENCIALLY smaller than ButtonBar and has
                        more elegant syntax. That's because it's
                        single-purpose. But the missing key support
                        is sad.

\\x <command>            this command will be prefixed by <prefix>
                        set in FIRST PART. The prefix is supposed to be
                        command and will be followed by space before
                        <command> is attached.

\\title                  this button cannot be executed. It will be in
                        pushed state all the time so that it will look
                        like menu titles.

@ENDNODE
@NODE AREXX

If you dont supply REXXPORT name (see above), no REXXPORT will be
created. ButtonBar understands following commands:

SLEEP   - ButtonBar goes to sleep, but stays in memory.
WAKEUP  - ButtonBar appears after being asleep.
QUIT    - ButtonBar quits and leaves all memory.
RESTART - ButtonBar closes all menus and rereads the menufile.

@ENDNODE
